# TestBase (Sync) Test Structure

Apply when writing or refactoring unit tests for code that has **no async methods** (mappers, managers, factories, static helpers, etc.). These inherit from `TestBase<TSubject>` and use a **synchronous** lifecycle: configure mocks and data in the **constructor**, then call `BuildSubject()` and optionally `ExecuteTestMethod()`.

## When to Use TestBase vs HandlerBase

- **TestBase&lt;TSubject&gt;** – Subject under test has no async API. No `IAsyncLifetime`; configure mocks and data in the constructor, then call `BuildSubject()` and `ExecuteTestMethod()`.
- **HandlerBase&lt;TSubject&gt;** – MediatR handler with async `Handle`. Uses `InitializeAsync` / `DisposeAsync`; configure mocks and test data in the constructor (runs before `InitializeAsync`).

## Class and Namespace

- **Test class**: `{Name}Tests` inheriting from `TestBase<{SubjectType}>` (e.g. `ExpenseDomainMapperTests : TestBase<ExpenseDomainMapper>`).
- **Namespace**: Mirror production (e.g. `MoneyManager.Core.Tests.Expenses`, `MoneyManager.Data.Tests.Mappers`).
- **Top of class**: One property per mocked dependency using `MockFor<T>()`. Omit if the subject has no dependencies.

## Constructor and Lifecycle

- **Constructor**: Configure mocks and test data (if any), then call `BuildSubject(); ExecuteTestMethod();` so the subject and any one-time results are ready before tests run.
- **BuildSubject()**: Builds the subject from mocks/dependencies.
- **ExecuteTestMethod()**: Override to run **once after** the subject is built (e.g. call the mapper once and store the result in a field for property-based `[Fact]` methods). Optional if tests call the subject directly in each test.

## Nested Classes (Same as Handler Tests)

- Use **nested classes** to group related facts (e.g. `Create`, `Update`, `DbToOutput` for mappers).
- Nested class inherits from the outer test class (e.g. `public class Create : ExpenseDomainMapperTests`).
- When a nested class overrides `ExecuteTestMethod()`, only that nested class's tests get that setup.

## Inputs and Default Returns

- **Input variables**: Define as **fields** or **static readonly** at class level.
- **Default return values**: Class-level fields used in `Setup(...)` and in assertions. Use **Fixture** for anonymous data where "any value" is enough.
- **Exception objects**: Class-level fields used in `Setup(...).Throws(_expectedException)` and `Assert.Throws<...>(() => ...); Assert.Same(_expectedException, ex);`.

## Setups – Only What the Scenario Uses

- For each test (or nested class), **only Setup the calls that actually occur** in that scenario.

## Prefer Concrete Values in Setups and Verifies

- Use **actual input/field values** in `Setup(...)` and `Verify(...)` instead of `It.IsAny` when you have that value.
- Use **It.IsAny** when asserting a method was **never** called: `Verify(..., Times.Never)`.

## Mapper-Style Tests (One Call, Many Property Assertions)

- In **ExecuteTestMethod()**: Call the subject once and store the result in a field.
- **`[Fact]` methods**: Assert one or a few properties each.

## Conventions

- **SubjectUnderTest**: Use for the instance under test; built by `BuildSubject()`.
- **Single logical assertion**: Prefer one logical assertion per test method.
- **Exception tests**: Use `Assert.Throws<T>(() => SubjectUnderTest.SomeMethod(...))` and assert the same exception instance when relevant.
- **No async**: Do not use `async`/`await` in test methods for TestBase-derived classes.
